The New Wealth List

Andrew Ross Sorkin=E2=80=99s annual DealBook has become the event of the ho=
liday season=E2=80=94the true heir to the Code Conference and an incredible=
 manifestation of Andrew=E2=80=99s rolodex. As you well know by now, Bezos,=
 Pichai, Bill Clinton, and even Alex Cooper made appearances. The crowd is =
nearly as august: Jeff Zucker, David Rhodes, Chris Licht, Peter Lattman, Li=
ev Schreiber, and Lance Armstrong, not to mention Dylan Byers and Eriq Gard=
er, both of whom presumably took the Puck Gulfstream into town. Fortunately=
 for me, I was able to enjoy a brisk walk from my place on the west side.

There were endless fascinating moments, of course, but two conversations, i=
n particular, are still on my mind. The first was Andrew=E2=80=99s intervie=
w with Sam Altman, the C.E.O. of
OpenAI, on the topic of his puny compensation. Altman may be among the co-f=
ounders of OpenAI, along with Elon Musk (net worth $353 billion), but he=E2=
=80=99s not particularly well paid. In fact, his pay is absurdly low, espec=
ially given that he=E2=80=99s running a company that has just raised new eq=
uity capital at a $157 billion valuation. In 2023, OpenAI paid Altman a ver=
y modest $76,000 a year. He also decided to take zero equity in OpenAI. Typ=
ically, you might expect a co-founder and C.E.O. to have 10 percent, maybe =
20 percent of the ownership of his or her company. Altman, in an era of ext=
reme C.E.O. indulgence, has forgone perhaps $30 billion or more. (Of course=
, that=E2=80=99s not to say he=E2=80=99s hurting: He=E2=80=99s worth about =
$2 billion, according to Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Billionaires Index, thanks to =
various investments, including a $1.4 billion stake in Reddit.)

Altman conceded that there has been =E2=80=9Csome investor pressure=E2=80=
=9D on him to take equity and, indeed, some
investors actually balked at backing OpenAI because he didn=E2=80=99t have =
skin in the game. Frankly, I don=E2=80=99t blame them. Not only is the rece=
nt valuation quite lofty, at $157 billion, but 99 out of 100 equity investo=
rs want to make sure a C.E.O.=E2=80=99s economic interests are perfectly al=
igned with theirs.

Andrew asked Sam if he regretted that decision. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t w=
ant it,=E2=80=9D he insisted. =E2=80=9CIf I could go back in time, I would =
have taken it, just some little bit, just to never have to answer this ques=
tion.=E2=80=9D That was a cute, flip answer, and it elicited some laughter =
from the audience. But then he elaborated on his thinking, which I found qu=
ite remarkable. =E2=80=9CNo matter how many times I try to explain to peopl=
e,=E2=80=9D he lamented, they don=E2=80=99t understand =E2=80=9CI have the =
most interesting, coolest job in the world.=E2=80=9D He called being C.E.O.=
 of OpenAI his =E2=80=9Cretirement dream=E2=80=9D of how to spend his time=
=E2=80=94Sam is 39 years old=E2=80=94after =E2=80=9Cwhat was a pretty good =
career=E2=80=9D starting a
few companies and working at Y Combinator. =E2=80=9CThis is my childhood dr=
eam job,=E2=80=9D he continued, referring to working on artificial intellig=
ence. =E2=80=9CAnd getting to sit in the room with the smartest researchers=
 in the world and go on this crazy adventure, that is what I always wanted =
to do. =E2=80=A6 And all of the weirdness aside, I think it should at least=
 be understandable that that is worth more to me than any additional money.=
