          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px;">
           <p style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>Andrew Ross Sorkin</b>=E2=
=80=99s annual DealBook has become <i>the</i> event of the holiday season=
=E2=80=94the true heir to the Code Conference and an incredible manifestati=
on of Andrew=E2=80=99s rolodex. As you well know by now, <b>Bezos</b>, <b>P=
ichai</b>, <b>Bill Clinton</b>, and even <b>Alex Cooper</b> made appearance=
s. The crowd is nearly as august: <b>Jeff Zucker</b>, <b>David Rhodes</b>, =
<b>Chris Licht</b>, <b>Peter Lattman</b>, <b>Liev Schreiber</b>, and <b>Lan=
ce Armstrong</b>, not to mention <b>Dylan Byers</b> and <b>Eriq Garder</b>,=
 both of whom presumably took the Puck Gulfstream into town. Fortunately fo=
r me, I was able to enjoy a brisk walk from my place on the west side.<br/>=
<br/>There were endless fascinating moments, of course, but two conversatio=
ns, in particular, are still on my mind. The first was Andrew=E2=80=99s int=
erview with <b>Sam Altman</b>, the C.E.O. of
OpenAI, on the topic of his puny compensation. Altman may be among the co-f=
ounders of OpenAI, along with <b>Elon Musk</b> (net worth $353 billion), bu=
t he=E2=80=99s not particularly well paid. In fact, his pay is absurdly low=
, especially given that he=E2=80=99s running a company that has just raised=
 new equity capital at a $157 billion valuation. In 2023, OpenAI paid Altma=
n a very modest $76,000 a year. He also decided to take <i>zero </i>equity =
in OpenAI. Typically, you might expect a co-founder and C.E.O. to have 10 p=
ercent, maybe 20 percent of the ownership of his or her company. Altman, in=
 an era of extreme C.E.O. indulgence, has forgone perhaps $30 billion or mo=
re. (Of course, that=E2=80=99s not to say he=E2=80=99s hurting: He=E2=80=99=
s worth about $2 billion, according to Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Billionaires Ind=
ex, thanks to various investments, including a $1.4 billion stake in Reddit=
=2E)<br/><br/>Altman conceded that t=
here has been =E2=80=9Csome investor pres=
sure=E2=80=9D on him to take equity and, indeed, some
investors actually balked at backing OpenAI because he didn=E2=80=99t have =
skin in the game. Frankly, I don=E2=80=99t blame them. Not only is the rece=
nt valuation quite lofty, at $157 billion, but 99 out of 100 equity investo=
rs want to make sure a C.E.O.=E2=80=99s economic interests are perfectly al=
igned with theirs.<br/><br/>Andrew asked Sam if he regretted that decision.=
 =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t want it,=E2=80=9D he insisted. =E2=80=9CIf I cou=
ld go back in time, I would have taken it, just some little bit, just to ne=
ver have to answer this question.=E2=80=9D That was a cute, flip answer, an=
d it elicited some laughter from the audience. But then he elaborated on hi=
s thinking, which I found quite remarkable. =E2=80=9CNo matter how many tim=
es I try to explain to people,=E2=80=9D he lamented, they don=E2=80=99t und=
erstand =E2=80=9CI have the most interesting, coolest job in the world.=E2=
=80=9D He called being C.E.O. of OpenAI his =E2=80=9Cretirement dream=E2=80=
=9D of how to spend his time=E2=80=94Sam is 39 years old=E2=80=94after =E2=
=80=9Cwhat was a pretty good career=E2=80=9D starting a
few companies and working at Y Combinator. =E2=80=9CThis is my childhood dr=
eam job,=E2=80=9D he continued, referring to working on artificial intellig=
ence. =E2=80=9CAnd getting to sit in the room with the smartest researchers=
 in the world and go on this crazy adventure, that is what I always wanted =
to do. =E2=80=A6 And all of the weirdness aside, I think it should at least=
 be understandable that that is worth more to me than any additional money.=
=E2=80=9D<br/></p>
          </td>
