x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Sitting at his boot=
h at Art Basel Miami Beach, <b>David Nahmad, </b>the eldest and leading mem=
ber of the transatlantic art dealing family, expressed regret for having so=
ld so many of his prized pieces years ago. Many of them have returned to ma=
rket for prices, he said, that were 10, 20, even 50 times higher. =E2=80=9C=
But you also have to bear in mind that the cash has lost its value,=E2=80=
=9D the patriarch said. =E2=80=9CFifty years ago, a painting worth $100,000=
 was a lot of money. Today, with $100,000, you can spend one week in a luxu=
ry hotel.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>I=E2=80=99m guessing Nahmad wasn=E2=80=99t sta=
ying at the Fontainebleau. In his interview with French journalist <b>Judit=
h Benhamou-Huet</b>, he lamented the dwindling supply of impressionist and =
modern masterpieces. His children wanted to sell, he said, but he preferred=
 to hold on to his art. Benhamou-Huet wondered why an
art dealer who didn=E2=80=99t want to sell his high-quality art had come to=
 an art fair. Nahmad <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9p=
